"""
MKT Context Commentary — Joshua chapters 9–11
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-joshua-9-11.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/joshua.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/joshua.json
- Amarna letters (14th c. BCE Canaanite city-state diplomacy)
- Yadin's Hazor excavations (Stratum XIII destruction layer)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch9: The deception succeeds because of Israel's failure to consult YHWH, not the Gibeonites' cleverness alone
- Ch10: The long day (vv12-14) is treated phenomenologically; multiple interpretive positions noted
- Ch10: Hanging on trees explained against Deut 21:22-23 background
- Ch11: Hamstringing horses signals theological warfare — YHWH, not cavalry, is Israel's strength
- Ch11: Anakite destruction resolves the Numbers 13 fear narrative
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOSHUA = {
  "9": {
    "1": '<p>The coalition of western kings — Hittites, Amorites, Canaanites, Perizzites, Hivites, Jebusites — represents the full ethnic spectrum of Canaan as catalogued in Deut 7:1-2. These nations were under the ḥērem proscription; the gathering of all of them against Israel at once signals that the narrator sees the conquest as a single decisive confrontation, not a series of local conflicts.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The phrase "joined forces with one purpose" (<em>yiqqāhălû</em>) describes a formal military alliance. In the Amarna letters (ca. 14th-13th c. BCE), Canaanite city-state rulers write to Pharaoh describing exactly these kinds of ad hoc coalitions — vassal kings pooling forces against a common threat. The pattern Israel faces was the normal regional power structure.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Gibeon contrasts sharply with the coalition. The Gibeonites were Hivites (v7), a Canaanite people marked for destruction under Deut 7:1-2. Their response to the news — not to fight but to seek terms — is portrayed as pragmatic rather than faithful. The narrator does not yet reveal whether their strategy will succeed.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The disguise draws on standard ANE diplomatic practice: envoys from distant nations would arrive with provisions provisioned for a long journey, carrying official documents or goods. The detail of worn sacks and cracked wineskins is a specific deception targeting Israelite treaty law, which permitted covenants with distant cities (Deut 20:10-15) but prohibited them with Canaanite nations (Deut 20:17-18).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The visual details accumulate to suggest extreme distance — patched sandals, old garments, dry crumbled bread. This was not an improvised disguise; the Gibeonites had researched Israelite covenant law well enough to know what signs would trigger treaty eligibility. The ruse exploits the gap between the letter of the law (distance of origin) and its spirit (the prohibition on Canaanite leagues).</p>',
    "6": '<p>Gilgal remained Israel\'s base of operations throughout the early campaign. The Gibeonites approach Joshua directly with a formal treaty request (<em>kərtû-lānû bərît</em>, "cut a covenant with us"). In ANE suzerain-vassal treaty language, the weaker party initiates by presenting themselves as servants. Their opening claim — "from a distant country" — is the critical legal category.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The Israelites\' immediate suspicion shows the leaders knew Deut 20:17-18 forbade covenants with Canaanites. "What if you live near us?" is the precise legal question: proximity would disqualify them from treaty eligibility. The leaders are not naive; they are suspicious but insufficiently diligent to seek YHWH\'s guidance.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"We are your servants" (<em>ʿăbādêkem ʾănaḥnû</em>) employs the formal language of treaty submission: the vassal presents himself as servant to the overlord. The same formula appears in diplomatic correspondence from Canaanite rulers to Pharaoh in the Amarna archive. Joshua\'s follow-up question about their origin is the right legal inquiry — he simply fails to take the next step of consulting the oracle.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The Gibeonites\' answer is strategically constructed: they invoke YHWH\'s reputation from events in Egypt and Transjordan (vv9-10) but conspicuously omit Jericho and Ai — events that would reveal they were local and had recent intelligence. The mention of Egypt and the Transjordan kings creates the impression of knowledge acquired from distant report, not near observation. Rahab used the same rhetorical move from the same regional knowledge base (Josh 2:9-10).</p>',
    "10": '<p>Sihon of Heshbon and Og of Bashan were the Transjordanian Amorite kings defeated in Numbers 21. Their defeat had already become the canonical proof of YHWH\'s power — they are cited repeatedly in Psalms and Deuteronomy. By confining their testimony to these events, the Gibeonites make themselves appear to be responding to rumors of the distant past rather than recent local news.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The Gibeonites claim their elders sent them — invoking the authority of their civic leadership. This mirrors ANE treaty protocol in which a city\'s elders, not just its king, participated in covenant ratification. The formal diplomatic framing — elder authorization, servant language, provision of food — follows recognized treaty conventions, making their claim structurally plausible.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Fresh bread — <em>leḥem ṣêdāh</em>, provisions for a journey — was a recognizable sign of recent departure. Presenting dry, crumbled bread as evidence of long travel was a specific material proof calibrated to Israelite inspection. The detail shows the Gibeonites understood that Israelite leaders would physically examine their goods rather than simply take their word.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The cracked wineskins, worn-out clothes, and patched sandals complete the physical evidence set. ANE caravans used skin-bottles whose cracking from temperature extremes over long journeys was a known phenomenon. The entire material case is coherent as a fabricated "proof kit" prepared before leaving Gibeon — the Gibeonites did not simply disguise themselves but carefully assembled evidence for the anticipated inspection.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The narrative hinge: "The Israelites sampled their provisions but did not consult the LORD." Consulting YHWH via the Urim and Thummim (Num 27:21) was the prescribed procedure for exactly this kind of major decision. The failure here directly parallels the failure at Ai (ch7) — in both cases, Israel acted on human assessment rather than divine inquiry. The Deuteronomic narrator makes the process failure, not the deception itself, the decisive point.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The treaty (<em>bərît</em>) was sealed with a sworn oath (<em>wayyiššābəʿû lāhem</em>). In ANE covenant law — and in Israelite theology — an oath sworn in the name of a deity was absolutely binding regardless of the circumstances under which it was made. Num 30:2 established that vows could not be broken. Even a covenant made under deception created binding obligations that could not be voided without incurring divine wrath (v20 invokes this). The leaders were trapped by their own lawful action.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The three-day revelation (cf. Jonah\'s three days, the three-day journey motifs in the Exodus narrative) means the treaty was already ratified before the deception was discovered. The geographical note — "these people lived nearby and were their neighbors" — uses precisely the language the Israelites feared in v7. The narrative irony is complete: their very question ("What if you live near us?") proved prophetic.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Gibeon, Chephirah, Beeroth, and Kiriath-jearim form a cluster of towns in the Benjaminite hill country northwest of Jerusalem. Their grouping suggests they were a confederacy — a Hivite city-state cluster. Kiriath-jearim is later known as the resting place of the ark of the covenant (1 Sam 7:1-2), suggesting these towns played a significant role in the tribal settlement that followed.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The assembly\'s grumbling (<em>wayyillōnû</em>) uses the same verb as the wilderness complaints against Moses (Exod 16:2, Num 14:2). The narrator signals that the people\'s reaction follows the pattern of the desert generation — not the faithful Joshua-Caleb pattern. The grumbling is directed against the leaders, who bear the institutional weight of the oath.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The leaders\' defense invokes the most serious available theological reason: violation of an oath sworn in YHWH\'s name would constitute perjury against YHWH himself, not merely against the Gibeonites. This is not diplomatic casuistry; it reflects the deep ANE conviction that oaths were witnessed and enforced by the deity invoked. Breaking this oath would invite divine punishment upon Israel itself.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The divine anger (<em>qeṣep</em>) anticipated here is precisely what erupts in 2 Sam 21: Saul\'s descendants are executed because he had violated this oath by attacking the Gibeonites. The narrator retrospectively validates the leaders\' logic. Covenant-breaking triggered the same theological consequences whether the original covenant was made wisely or foolishly.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Woodcutters and water-carriers (<em>ḥōṭəbê ʿēṣîm wəšōʾăbê mayim</em>) were the lowest servile roles in the ancient economy, typically performed by corvée laborers or prisoners of war. The Gibeonites\' status in this assignment — permanent temple service at the altar — is a form of integration into the Israelite cultic economy: they are not destroyed, but they are perpetually subordinate. Deut 29:11 lists "your woodcutters and water-carriers" alongside the covenant community, suggesting their inclusion in the covenant people was acknowledged even as their servile status persisted.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Joshua\'s direct confrontation addresses the deception on its own terms. "Why did you deceive us?" does not question the validity of the treaty — that was already determined — but it does hold the Gibeonites accountable for their method. ANE treaty law recognized that fraud in treaty formation was reprehensible even where the resulting covenant remained binding.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Cursed" (<em>ʾărûrîm</em>) echoes the curse language of Gen 9:25 (Ham\'s son Canaan: "cursed be Canaan — a servant of servants"). The Gibeonites\' servile status is connected to the broader Canaanite curse tradition. The specific form — woodcutters and water-carriers for "the house of my God" — transforms what could be mere slave status into temple service, a form of perpetual religious incorporation.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The Gibeonites\' explanation reveals their full knowledge of Deut 7:1-2 and 20:17. They had heard the exact content of the law — the command to destroy the Canaanites — and knew their only option for survival was to circumvent it legally. Their fear (<em>wayyîrāʾû</em>) is the same word used of Rahab (2:9) and the Canaanite nations generally. The fear of YHWH drives even the nations to seek refuge within Israel\'s covenant sphere, by whatever means available.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"Whatever you think is good and right" (<em>kaṭṭôb wəkayyāšār bəʿênêkā</em>) is a formal submission formula placing the petitioner entirely in the overlord\'s hands. The Gibeonites are not arguing their case; they are throwing themselves on the mercy of the suzerain. This is complete covenant surrender — the language of total vassalage.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Joshua\'s protection of the Gibeonites against the assembly\'s desire for violence demonstrates the binding force of the sworn covenant even over popular pressure. The leaders\' authority to uphold an oath superseded the congregation\'s desire for revenge. This sets a precedent: covenant obligations protect even those who obtained them through deception, once legitimately ratified.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"At whatever place the LORD would choose" anticipates the centralization theology of Deuteronomy — the single place of worship where YHWH would set his name (Deut 12:5). The Gibeonites\' service at the LORD\'s altar gives them a perpetual place in the Israelite cult even as a subordinate class. "To this day" is a standard authorial time-marker indicating the arrangement persisted into the narrator\'s own period — likely during the monarchy.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "1": '<p>Adonizedek ("my lord is Zedek/righteousness") is a throne name in the same pattern as Melchizedek ("king of Zedek/righteousness") from Gen 14:18. Jerusalem (Salem) already had a priestly-royal tradition centered on the deity Zedek before the Israelite conquest. The king is alarmed not by military defeat but by political defection: Gibeon, a major city, has transferred its allegiance to Israel.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Gibeon\'s strategic importance: the text describes it as "like one of the royal cities, greater than Ai." Archaeological surveys confirm Gibeon (modern el-Jib) was a significant site with a large water system — the famous "pool of Gibeon" (2 Sam 2:13) — and substantial storage capacity. Its men were "warriors" (<em>gibbôrê ḥāyil</em>), trained soldiers. Losing Gibeon to the Israelite camp represented a major shift in the regional balance of power.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Adonizedek\'s coalition-building mirrors the Amarna correspondence: Canaanite city-state rulers regularly sent urgent letters to Pharaoh and to each other requesting military assistance. Hoham, Piram, Japhia, and Debir represent the major cities of the central and southern Shephelah — a coordinated response by the major powers of the region. The cities named (Hebron, Jarmuth, Lachish, Eglon) controlled the key routes of the southern hill country.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Come and help me attack Gibeon" (<em>ʿălû ʾēlay wəʿizrûnî wənakkeh ʾet-gibʿôn</em>): the direct summons uses military alliance language. The stated reason — "it has made peace with Joshua" — signals that Gibeon\'s defection was seen as treachery deserving punishment. In ANE political culture, a subordinate city switching allegiances to an enemy power was an act of rebellion against the dominant alliance, justifying punitive military action.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The five Amorite kings form one of the most powerful coalitions the conquest narrative describes. Amorite is used here as a comprehensive term for the ruling class of Canaanite city-states (cf. Gen 15:16: "the sin of the Amorites"). The siege of Gibeon puts the treaty Israel just made to an immediate test — can/will Israel defend its newly acquired vassal?</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Gibeonite appeal "do not abandon your servants" (<em>ʾal-terep yādêkā mēʿăbādêkā</em>) uses the suzerain-vassal covenant formula. Having entered the covenant relationship, Gibeon now invokes the lord\'s obligation to protect its vassals. This is a recognized feature of ANE suzerainty treaties: the great king promised military defense of his vassals in exchange for their loyalty and tribute. Israel was now bound to fulfill this obligation.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Joshua\'s immediate response — marching from Gilgal — demonstrates covenant faithfulness. The military deployment of "all his best warriors" (<em>kol-ʿam hammilyāmāh gibbôrê heḥāyil</em>) signals this was a full-scale military response, not merely a token show of force. The speed of response (overnight march, v9) reflects both military necessity and covenant urgency.</p>',
    "8": '<p>YHWH\'s assurance to Joshua before battle — "I have given them into your hand" — repeats the formula that preceded Jericho (6:2) and Ai (8:1, 18). The divine word before battle is a commissioning oracle that defines the engagement as a sacred act, not merely a military operation. The oracle preempts fear and establishes divine guaranty before any human action.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The overnight march from Gilgal covers approximately 25-30 km uphill through the Wadi Qilt region. This was an extreme physical demand — the kind of forced night march that sacrifices rest for tactical surprise. The surprise attack (<em>petaʾ</em>, suddenly) exploits the advantage of unexpected approach. Military historians note that ancient sieges were vulnerable to relief forces that arrived before the besiegers had consolidated their positions.</p>',
    "10": '<p>YHWH "threw them into panic" (<em>wayhummēm YHWH</em>): the verb <em>hāmam</em> appears also in Exod 14:24 (YHWH throws the Egyptian army into panic at the Red Sea) and Judg 4:15 (Sisera\'s army). It describes a sudden confusion and terror that disrupts military cohesion. The divine warrior motif is explicit: YHWH is the primary agent; Israel is the instrument. The route of flight from Gibeon to Makkedah via Beth-horon traces the topography of the descent from the central highlands — a natural escape route that became a killing field.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Hailstones as divine weapons appear in Ugaritic mythological texts (Baal deploys storm weapons against Yam/Mot) and Egyptian battle accounts (Merenptah\'s inscriptions invoke divine meteorological intervention). The narrator here presents YHWH using the same atmospheric arsenal — but for Israel\'s deliverance, not in mythological combat. The comparative note ("more died from hailstones than from the sword") reinforces that the human military contribution was secondary to the divine act.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Joshua\'s command to the sun and moon is addressed publicly ("in the sight of Israel"). This is a prayer in the form of a command — comparable to Elijah\'s prayer on Carmel (1 Kgs 18:36-37) in its confident imperative address to YHWH. The Book of Jashar from which this is quoted was apparently a collection of heroic poetry celebrating Israel\'s wars (also cited in 2 Sam 1:18 for David\'s lament over Saul). The astronomical frame — sun over Gibeon, moon over Aijalon — suggests a specific time of day and directional orientation.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Three main interpretive positions on the long day have been advanced: (1) A miraculous extension of daylight allowing the battle to continue; (2) A solar eclipse that brought unusual darkness and coolness (interpreted as the sun "stopping" its heat rather than its motion); (3) Poetic/hyperbolic language from the Jashar source celebrating total victory. The text\'s own emphasis falls less on the astronomical mechanism than on the theological claim in v14: "the LORD listened to a human voice" — an unprecedented divine responsiveness to Joshua\'s prayer.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"There has never been a day like it before or since" is a superlative formula used for events of unique theological significance (cf. 2 Kgs 23:25 for Josiah\'s Passover). The narrator\'s primary claim is not astronomical but relational: YHWH "listened to a human voice" and "fought for Israel." The day is paradigmatic — it defines what YHWH-warfare looks like at its most intense. Parallels to Exod 14 (YHWH fighting at the sea) are deliberate: both are salvation events where Israel does not win by its own strength.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The brief notice of Joshua\'s return to Gilgal interrupts the narrative; many commentators note that v43 repeats this return after the cave episode (vv16-27), suggesting v15 may be a displaced conclusion or an editorial seam. Gilgal remains the ritual center — Joshua returns to base before the next campaign phase.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The five kings hiding in the cave at Makkedah introduces a sub-episode within the larger battle narrative. Cave hiding was standard ANE military practice for routed commanders — archaeological surveys in the Shephelah confirm numerous natural cave systems. The specific cave at Makkedah became a monument: the stones placed at its entrance (v18) and the final sealing (v27) are authoritatively noted "to this day."</p>',
    "17": '<p>The intelligence system that located the kings reflects the organized military structure of Joshua\'s campaign. Pursuit and mopping up were standard ancient warfare doctrine — letting defeated commanders escape to rally forces was a recognized danger. The rapid report to Joshua and his equally rapid response (v18) shows efficient command-and-control.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The command to seal the cave with large stones and post guards while the pursuit continued was tactically shrewd: the kings were contained without diverting the main force from completing the rout. This is the kind of operational detail that lends the narrative historical texture — the narrator shows awareness of the trade-offs between securing prisoners and maintaining pursuit momentum.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"Cut off their retreat" (<em>qiṣṣû ʾet-zənābām</em>, lit. "cut off their tails") is a military idiom for cutting off a retreating force\'s rear guard — preventing them from reaching fortified cities where they could be reinforced. The theological note follows the tactical instruction: "the LORD your God has handed them over to you." Divine action does not remove human tactical execution; it guarantees its success.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The "tremendous defeat" (<em>makkāh gəḏôlāh məʾōḏ</em>) is qualified: "the survivors having taken refuge in the fortified cities." The conquest was not absolute in this engagement — survivors escaped. This is historiographically honest: the narrator acknowledges that the southern coalition was broken but not completely eliminated. The fortified cities would need to be taken individually in the sweep of vv28-43.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"No one dared to say a word against the Israelites" (<em>lōʾ-ḥāraṣ liBənê yiśrāʾēl</em>, lit. "no one sharpened his tongue against") is a formulaic expression of complete intimidation — the military victory extended to psychological and political domination. The camp at Makkedah became the staging point for the subsequent southern campaign.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The ceremonial extraction of the five kings from the cave converts a military necessity into a theological ritual. Joshua\'s command — "bring out those five kings to me" — echoes the language of judicial proceedings. What follows (vv24-27) is a formal ritual of conquest: humiliation, public declaration, execution, and burial.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The five kings represent five of the most important Canaanite city-states: Jerusalem (Jebusite royal city, not yet captured), Hebron (associated with the Anakim), Jarmuth (southwestern highlands), Lachish (major fortress city), Eglon (Shephelah). Their combined defeat represents the collapse of organized Canaanite resistance in the south.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"Put your feet on the necks of these kings" is the enactment of a widely attested ANE iconographic motif: Egyptian pharaohs are depicted with feet on the necks of prostrate Canaanite prisoners; Assyrian reliefs show similar imagery. The act was not improvised cruelty but a formal ritual of conquest — complete submission of the defeated, public display of the victor\'s authority. Joshua\'s direction that the commanders perform this act (not Joshua himself) extends the symbolism: all Israel shares the victory.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The exhortation "do not be afraid or discouraged; be strong and courageous" repeats the commissioning language of Josh 1:6-7, 9 and Deut 31:6-7. This is deliberate: Joshua is now speaking to his commanders the same words YHWH and Moses had spoken to him. The rhetoric of holy war assured leaders that YHWH\'s commitment to defeat all enemies was not exhausted by this one engagement — this was the pattern for all future conquests.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The killing of the kings and hanging on five trees (or one tree, depending on reading) follows Deut 21:22-23: "if a man guilty of a capital offense is put to death and you hang his body on a pole..." The Deuteronomic law prohibited leaving bodies on display overnight — they were hanged after death as public shame, and the land would be defiled if they remained until morning. Joshua follows the law exactly in v27, taking them down at sunset.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The cave becomes a permanent monument: the "large stones at the entrance of the cave" and the "to this day" formula mark this as a recognized historical landmark in the narrator\'s time. The cave that served as the kings\' hiding place becomes their tomb — a reversal of the royal burial custom (elaborate tombs as monuments to power) into a mark of defeat. The sunset timing is precisely Deut 21:23.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The sweep of southern cities (vv28-43) is presented in highly formulaic language: capture, sword, total destruction, king treated as previous kings. This formulaic style is typical of ANE campaign annals (Egyptian victory inscriptions, Assyrian annals) where each city\'s conquest is recorded with stereotyped verbs. The repetition signals completeness — no significant city in the southern campaign was exempted from the same treatment.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Libnah is identified with Tell Bornat or Tell es-Safi (the later Gath). The campaign moves west from Makkedah toward the Shephelah — the lowland foothills that formed the strategic buffer zone between the Philistine coastal plain and the Judean highlands. This region would remain contested for centuries; the Philistines would hold it against Israel even after the initial conquest.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The formula "handed over to Israel" (<em>wayyittēn YHWH gam-ʾōtāh</em>) is repeated for each city — the divine subject (YHWH) is grammatically the active agent of conquest in every instance. This is the narrator\'s theological framing: the military victories are listed as acts of YHWH, with Joshua as the human instrument. The comparison to Jericho sets each new conquest against the paradigmatic first victory.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Lachish was one of the most heavily fortified cities in Canaan and would remain strategically critical throughout the biblical period. Sennacherib\'s siege of Lachish (701 BCE) was considered important enough to be commemorated in a massive relief at his Nineveh palace. Archaeological excavation of Lachish (Tell ed-Duweir) reveals multiple destruction layers; the Late Bronze Age destruction is consistent with the conquest narrative.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The "second day" capture of Lachish is a specific chronological detail unusual in the formulaic sweep. It may reflect the relative difficulty of taking Lachish compared to other cities — its fortifications required a sustained assault. The detail suggests the narrator had access to specific campaign records, not merely theological summaries.</p>',
    "33": '<p>Horam king of Gezer\'s intervention creates a brief break in the formulaic sweep. Gezer was a major Canaanite city in the northern Shephelah controlling the road between Jerusalem and the coast. Its attempt to relieve Lachish — and its destruction — extended the southern campaign\'s reach but notably did not result in Israel capturing Gezer itself. Gezer remained unconquered until Solomon\'s time (1 Kgs 9:16).</p>',
    "34": '<p>Eglon (Tell ʿĒtûn or Tell el-Ḥesi) was one of the five coalition cities. Its capture continues the systematic elimination of the southern alliance. The "surrounding" (<em>wayyaḥanû ʿālêhā</em>) indicates a formal siege rather than a surprise assault — the campaign adapted tactics to each city\'s defensive situation.</p>',
    "35": '<p>"That same day" (<em>bayyôm hahûʾ</em>) occurs repeatedly in the sweep (also v28) suggesting rapid sequential captures. This campaign pace — multiple cities in rapid succession — may reflect the collapse of organized resistance after the defeat of the five kings. With their military leadership eliminated, individual cities may have had limited capacity to mount sustained defense.</p>',
    "36": '<p>Hebron was the major city of the southern highlands, associated with the patriarchs (Gen 23:2 — Abraham buried Sarah at Machpelah near Hebron). It was also the city of Arba, father of Anak (Josh 14:15), making it the center of the Anakim — the giant-clans that had terrorized the spies in Num 13:33. Its capture is therefore symbolically weighted beyond its military significance.</p>',
    "37": '<p>The destruction of Hebron and its "king" is formulaically identical to earlier cities. The specific mention of "surrounding towns" (<em>bənōtêhā</em>, lit. "its daughters") — outlying villages dependent on the main city — reflects the ANE system of city-states that controlled agricultural hinterlands. Total conquest required eliminating both the city center and its dependent settlements.</p>',
    "38": '<p>Debir (Kiriath-Sepher, identified with Tell Beit Mirsim) was a scribal center — its name means "the back/inner sanctuary" or possibly "the Word/Oracle." It was later specifically associated with Caleb\'s clan and Othniel\'s capture of the city as a bride-price for Caleb\'s daughter (Josh 15:15-17). The detailed tradition surrounding Debir\'s capture by Othniel supplements the formulaic account here.</p>',
    "39": '<p>The comparison formula — "as he had treated Hebron and Libnah with their kings" — links each new conquest to previous ones, building a chain of precedent. This is not mere repetition but a claim of consistent, principled action: Joshua applies the same standard of total destruction to each city, without favoritism or exception. The consistency is the theological point — the ḥērem (devoted destruction) was not arbitrary violence but a principled execution of divine command.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The summary statement covers all geographical zones: hill country, Negev, western foothills, mountain slopes. This is the standard fourfold geographical division of Canaan west of the Jordan. "All their kings" — the leadership structure of Canaanite city-states — was systematically eliminated. "He left no survivors" repeats the ḥērem formula. The grounding is explicit: "as the LORD God of Israel had commanded" (Deut 20:17).</p>',
    "41": '<p>Kadesh-barnea to Gaza marks the southern boundary; Goshen (not Egyptian Goshen but a region near Debir) to Gibeon marks the northern limit of this phase. This delineates the territory of the southern campaign as distinct from the later northern campaign of ch11. The geographical precision — with named boundary markers — has the character of an official military summary rather than a theological gloss.</p>',
    "42": '<p>"In one campaign" (<em>pəʿam ʾeḥāt</em>) is the key claim: the entire southern coalition was broken in a single sustained offensive. ANE campaign records often distinguished between multi-year campaigns and single-season operations. The narrator presents the speed of the conquest as itself evidence of divine agency — what would normally take years happened in one campaign "because the LORD, the God of Israel, fought for Israel."</p>',
    "43": '<p>The return to Gilgal closes the chapter with the same ritual base that served throughout the campaigns. Gilgal was the site of the initial covenant renewal (circumcision, Passover, ch5) and remained the anchor point of the campaign. Returning there between operations maintained the covenant framework that gave the campaign its meaning.</p>'
  },
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>Jabin king of Hazor likely a throne title: another "Jabin" reigns in Hazor during the period of the judges (Judg 4:2), suggesting the name was dynastic. Hazor (Tell el-Qedaḥ) was the largest city in Canaan — Yadin\'s excavations revealed a site of approximately 200 acres with a population estimated at 20,000-40,000 at its peak. The Amarna letters mention Hazor as a major commercial and political center with direct correspondence to Pharaoh. Its prominence meant that subduing Hazor meant breaking the backbone of northern Canaanite power.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The geography of the northern coalition stretches from the Galilee highlands (hill country), the Jordan rift valley (Arabah/Kinnereth), the coastal plain (western foothills), and the Carmel range (heights of Dor). This is a comprehensive listing of all northern zones — the narrator signals that the entire northern tier of Canaan is mobilized against Israel, a greater challenge than the southern campaign.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The ethnic catalogue — Canaanites, Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Jebusites, Hivites — matches the standard list of Deut 7:1. The inclusion of Hivites "below Hermon in the region of Mizpah" extends the coalition to the far north, near the Anti-Lebanon range. The comprehensiveness of the list underscores the theological point: all the nations under the ḥērem are gathered together for a single decisive confrontation.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"As numerous as the sand on the seashore" (<em>kəḥôl ʾăšer ʿal-śəpat-hayyām lārōb</em>) is the epic formula for an uncountable host (cf. Gen 22:17, Judg 7:12, 1 Sam 13:5). The addition of "horses and chariots" is specifically significant: chariots were the Bronze Age equivalent of tank warfare — a technology Israel lacked and which the spies had used as a reason for fear (Num 13:28-29 mentions fortified cities; the Amarna-era Canaanites maintained chariot forces).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The Waters of Merom (possibly Lake Huleh or a nearby stream in upper Galilee) was chosen by the northern coalition as an assembly point — a militarily defensible staging area for a combined force. Ancient Near Eastern warfare typically began with coalition assembly before the main engagement; the Merom meeting was the preliminary concentration before the planned offensive against Israel.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The command to hamstring horses (<em>ʿaqēr ʾet-sûsêhem</em>) and burn chariots is counter-strategic from a conventional military standpoint — Israel could have used these assets. The theological logic follows Deut 17:16 ("the king must not acquire great numbers of horses for himself") and Ps 20:7 ("some trust in chariots and horses, but we trust in the name of YHWH"). YHWH explicitly commands Israel not to capitalize on their battlefield advantage, because trust in military technology would displace trust in YHWH. The victory is to be won in a way that cannot be attributed to superior weaponry.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A surprise attack at the Waters of Merom — again a forced march for tactical surprise, as at Gibeon (10:9). The pattern of sudden, unexpected attack is Joshua\'s consistent tactical signature throughout the campaign. Ancient military theorists (including those behind ANE strategic texts like the Hittite military instructions) recognized that psychological surprise could negate numerical superiority.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The pursuit extends north to Greater Sidon (the Phoenician coast) and south through the Huleh valley to Mizpah — an enormous geographic spread covering essentially all of northern Canaan. "Until no survivor was left" is the ḥērem formula, here applied to a pursuing force rather than a siege. The geographic extent of the pursuit signals a complete military collapse, not merely a battlefield defeat.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Joshua\'s exact obedience — hamstringing horses and burning chariots exactly as commanded — is the compliance formula that recurs throughout Joshua\'s narrative. The narrator emphasizes not just what Joshua did but that he did it "just as the LORD had told him." This refrain (climactically stated in v15) is the central historiographical claim: Joshua\'s generation completed what Moses commanded.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Hazor is specifically singled out for special treatment: Joshua "turned back" to capture it after the main pursuit, and burned it alone among the northern cities (v13). The text notes that Hazor "had formerly been the leading city among all those kingdoms" — its destruction was symbolic as well as military. Yadin\'s excavation uncovered a massive Late Bronze Age destruction layer at Hazor Stratum XIII, which many archaeologists date to the 13th century BCE, though the exact identification with the Joshua narrative remains debated.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The ḥērem of Hazor — every human killed, the city burned — contrasts with the treatment of other northern cities (v13: cities on their mounds not burned). Hazor was the cultic and political center of northern Canaan; its complete destruction eliminated the ideological infrastructure of Canaanite religion in the north. Archaeological evidence from Hazor shows destruction of temples and cult objects specifically, consistent with anti-cultic intent.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Just as Moses the servant of the LORD had commanded" is the compliance formula that anchors every act of conquest in the Mosaic law. The phrase "Moses the servant of the LORD" is the standard Deuteronomistic honorific — the title that will be transferred to Joshua at his death (Josh 24:29). By attributing the conquest to Moses\'s command, the narrator places it entirely within the covenant framework of Sinai.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Cities built on their mounds" (<em>hāʿārîm hāʿōmədôt ʿal-tillām</em>) — the Hebrew <em>tel</em> (tell) refers to the accumulated debris of successive occupation layers that forms the characteristic mound-shaped archaeological site. Not burning these cities was both practical (they could be settled immediately) and legally permitted — the ḥērem applied to inhabitants and cult objects, not necessarily to all physical infrastructure. Only Hazor, as the dominant cultic center, received full destruction.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The Israelites kept the livestock and plunder — items not under the ḥērem (cf. the contrast with Achan in ch7, who took items that were under the ban). The ḥērem applied specifically to people and cult objects, not to all property. The distinction is legally precise: Israel enriched itself materially from the conquest while adhering to the prohibition on making covenants with or allowing the survival of the Canaanite population.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The compliance chain is the theological climax of the northern campaign: "as the LORD had commanded his servant Moses, so Moses had commanded Joshua, and Joshua carried it out — he left nothing undone of all the LORD had commanded Moses." This three-link chain (YHWH → Moses → Joshua) mirrors the chain in Josh 1:1-9 and closes the first half of the book. The claim is total and deliberate: no command was left unfulfilled. This is the standard by which Israel\'s later failures in Judges will be measured.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The geographical summary (vv16-20) enumerates the land Joshua took using the same zones as the campaign summaries: hill country, Negev, Goshen, western foothills, Arabah, and the hill countries of Israel and Judah. The breadth covers essentially the entire territory west of the Jordan that the book will later distribute by lot. This summary functions as a "before the distribution" inventory establishing what has been claimed.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The boundary markers — "from Mount Halak toward Seir" (southern boundary in the Negev highlands) to "Baal-gad in the Lebanon Valley" (northern boundary at the foot of Hermon) — define the full extent of Israelite territory from maximum south to maximum north. This is the ideal territory that will never be fully settled; Judges will document the gradual erosion of these boundaries as Israel failed to maintain the conquest.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"Joshua waged war against all these kings for a long time" (<em>yāmîm rabbîm</em>, many days) is an important qualification: the conquest was not a single dramatic sweep but an extended campaign. The formulaic summaries of chs 10-11 compress what was a prolonged operation. This note provides temporal realism against a reading that imagines instantaneous conquest — the land was taken over years, not days.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The Gibeonites are the sole exception to the total-conquest claim: "not a single city made peace with the Israelites" except for the Hivite Gibeonite confederation (9:3-15). The verb "made peace" (<em>hiśliymāh šālôm</em>) uses the same root as Gibeon\'s treaty: šālôm. The irony is deliberate — Gibeon survived precisely because it sought peace when all other nations chose war.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"The LORD who hardened their hearts" (<em>mēʾēt YHWH hāyəṯāh ḥazzēq ʾet-libbām</em>) echoes the hardening of Pharaoh\'s heart in the Exodus narrative (Exod 4:21, 14:4). The theological claim is that the nations\' decision to fight — rather than seek terms — was divinely ordained so that they might be brought under the ḥērem. This is not a denial of human agency but a claim of divine sovereignty over the outcome: YHWH arranged that no alternative path (surrender, negotiation) would interrupt the execution of the ban. The parallel to Pharaoh suggests this was a deliberate structural parallel: just as Egypt was hardened so that YHWH\'s power would be demonstrated, so the Canaanite nations were hardened so that the land could be fully cleared.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The Anakim (<em>hāʿănāqîm</em>) were the giant-clans whose presence in the land had caused the spies to despair in Num 13:33 ("we seemed like grasshoppers in our own eyes"). Their specific cities — Hebron (home of Arba, "father of Anak," Josh 14:15), Debir, Anab — were the very sites the spies feared. Joshua\'s elimination of the Anakim from the hill country of Judah and Israel resolves the narrative thread left hanging from the spy mission: the generation that feared giants is gone; the new generation under Joshua destroys them.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The survivors — "in Gaza, Gath, and Ashdod" — escaped into Philistine territory. This is a forward-pointing narrative note: these cities were not under Israelite control, and the giants who survived there would resurface in later Israelite history. Goliath was from Gath (1 Sam 17:4); his brothers were also giants (2 Sam 21:15-22). The note is historically honest and narratively significant — the Anakite threat was reduced but not eliminated.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Joshua took the entire land" (<em>wayyiqqaḥ yəhôšuaʿ ʾet-kol-hāʾāreṣ</em>) is the conquest\'s summary claim. "Just as the LORD had told Moses" anchors it in the covenant promise (Gen 12:7, 15:18-21, Deut 1:8). "He gave it as an inheritance to Israel according to their tribal divisions" anticipates the distribution of chs 13-21. And "the land had rest from war" (<em>šāqaṭāh hāʾāreṣ mimmilyāmāh</em>) is the Sabbath-rest motif: the land enters its šābat, the cessation of conflict that the creation narrative associated with divine completion (Gen 2:2-3). This rest is real but incomplete — Judges will show that the land\'s rest depended on Israel\'s faithfulness, and that faithfulness would fail.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua')
    merge_comm(existing, JOSHUA)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua', existing)
    print('Joshua 9-11 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
